    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "The Supreme Leader of Iran is chosen by the Assembly of Experts.\n\nThis market will resolve according to the person who is named as the next Supreme Leader of the Islamic Republic of Iran.\n\nThe resolution of this market will be based on the first official announcement of the next Supreme Leader of Iran after Ali Khamenei.\n\nAny interim, acting, or temporary leader will not count toward the resolution of this market.\n\nIf Ali Khamenei remains the Supreme Leader of Iran or the next Supreme Leader of Iran is not officially announced by June 30, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, this market will resolve to “None by June 30”.\n\nIf the position of Supreme Leader is formally abolished — including instances in which the Islamic Republic of Iran ceases to exist, is replaced, or no longer maintains the office of Supreme Leader — this market will resolve to “Position abolished”.\n\nOnly individuals formally appointed to the office titled “Supreme Leader of the Islamic Republic of Iran” (or a clearly direct constitutional equivalent replacing that title) will qualify. Individuals serving solely as President, head of state, head of government, or in any other role that is not explicitly the Supreme Leader or a direct constitutional equivalent will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution source will be official information from the government of Iran. A consensus of credible reporting may also be used.",
    "outcome": "Mojtaba Khamenei",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThe selection of Mojtaba Khamenei as the new Supreme Leader of Iran was precipitated by the sudden death of his father, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, during US-Israeli airstrikes in late February 2026. Following the assassination, a temporary three-person leadership council managed the country's affairs while pressure mounted on the Assembly of Experts to swiftly ensure leadership continuity. Facing wartime conditions and the need for internal stability, the Assembly of Experts convened and swiftly appointed Mojtaba Khamenei on March 8, 2026, consolidating the hardline faction's power and continuing his father's legacy.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **February 28, 2026 - March 1, 2026:** Ayatollah Ali Khamenei is killed in a pre-dawn US-Israeli airstrike on Tehran, as announced by US President Donald Trump and confirmed by Iranian state media [art_general_20260228_004_1c26bb05].\n- **March 4, 2026:** A temporary leadership council comprising President Masoud Pezeshkian, Chief Justice Gholam-Hossein Mohseni-Eje'i, and Ayatollah Alireza Arafi assumes wartime leadership duties to juggle the conflict and the looming succession [art_general_20260304_009_19b535c1].\n- **March 7, 2026:** Senior clerics, including Grand Ayatollah Naser Makarem Shirazi, push the 88-member Assembly of Experts to convene and select a new supreme leader within 24 hours to stabilize the nation [art_general_20260307_014_b9da880e].\n- **March 8, 2026:** The Assembly of Experts officially names Mojtaba Khamenei as the new Supreme Leader of Iran, succeeding his father [art_general_20260308_007_8871eb45] [art_general_20260308_003_6b7b52d2].\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\n- **Root Cause (The Assassination):** The unprecedented US-Israeli airstrikes on Tehran resulted in the sudden death of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei [art_general_20260228_004_1c26bb05]. This immediately created a massive power vacuum at the pinnacle of Iran's political and religious hierarchy.\n- **Intermediate Mechanism (Temporary Leadership & Urgency):** In response to the crisis, a temporary council led by political and judicial hardliners took over [art_general_20260304_009_19b535c1]. The ongoing conflict with the US and Israel created immense pressure to project stability and unity, prompting senior clerics to demand a rapid succession process [art_general_20260307_014_b9da880e].\n- **Proximate Trigger (Assembly of Experts Decision):** The 88-member Assembly of Experts met under these extraordinary wartime conditions. Prioritizing continuity of the hardline ideological establishment and leveraging Mojtaba's existing immense behind-the-scenes influence within the security and clerical apparatus, they selected him to replace his father.\n- **Final Outcome:** State media officially announced Mojtaba Khamenei as the new Supreme Leader on March 8, 2026 [art_general_20260308_007_8871eb45].\n\n## Countervailing Factors\n- **US Opposition:** Former US President Donald Trump publicly warned that Iran's next leader \"won't last long\" if he does not meet US approval [art_general_20260308_012_1b3ce05c]. This external threat aimed to deter the selection of another hardliner but instead likely reinforced the regime's resolve to quickly consolidate power behind a known, defiant figure.\n- **Alternative Candidates:** Figures like Ayatollah Alireza Arafi, who was part of the temporary leadership council, were plausible alternatives [art_general_20260304_009_19b535c1]. However, Mojtaba's deep ties to the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) and his father's inner circle ultimately outweighed Arafi's immediate prominence.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: US-Israeli airstrikes kill Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei\n  - Date: February 28, 2026\n  - Why it matters: Created the vacancy that required a succession.\n  - Source: [art_general_20260228_004_1c26bb05]\n- E2: Temporary leadership council assumes wartime control\n  - Date: March 4, 2026\n  - Why it matters: Managed the immediate crisis and set the stage for a managed, hardline succession.\n  - Source: [art_general_20260304_009_19b535c1]\n- E3: Clerics pressure Assembly of Experts for swift decision\n  - Date: March 7, 2026\n  - Why it matters: Forced an accelerated timeline for the selection process.\n  - Source: [art_general_20260307_014_b9da880e]\n- E4: Assembly of Experts names Mojtaba Khamenei Supreme Leader\n  - Date: March 8, 2026\n  - Why it matters: The official act resolving the succession.\n  - Source: [art_general_20260308_007_8871eb45], [art_general_20260308_003_6b7b52d2]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Ali Khamenei killed in airstrikes | [art_general_20260228_004_1c26bb05] | 2026-02-28 | 1.0 | Confirmed by US and Iranian sources. |\n| Temporary council takes charge | [art_general_20260304_009_19b535c1] | 2026-03-04 | 1.0 | Arafi, Pezeshkian, Mohseni-Eje'i manage transition. |\n| Pressure for 24-hour decision | [art_general_20260307_014_b9da880e] | 2026-03-07 | 1.0 | Driven by wartime instability. |\n| Mojtaba Khamenei named Supreme Leader | [art_general_20260308_007_8871eb45], [art_general_20260308_003_6b7b52d2] | 2026-03-08 | 1.0 | State media officially reports the decision. |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\n- **Internal Resistance:** It remains slightly uncertain how much internal opposition Mojtaba faced within the Assembly of Experts, given the secretive nature of the body.\n- **Alternative Path:** Had the temporary council failed to maintain order, a direct military takeover by the IRGC, potentially sidelining the clerical establishment entirely or installing a more pliant figurehead like Arafi, was a plausible alternative scenario.\n",
